Enel, Eni, Monti Ascensori, STM, Trevi May Be Active: Italy Equity Preview

-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 
2011-06-09T06:49:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/enel-eni-monti-ascensori-stm-trevi-may-be-active-italy-equity-preview.html
The following companies may be active
in Italian trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and share
prices are from the previous close.  Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index (FTSEMIB)  fell 297.21, or 1.4
percent, to 20,277.28.  Azimut Holding SpA (AZM)  : Gruppo Banca Leonardo trimmed
its price estimate to 9 euros from 10.5 euros, while Equita Sim
SpA cut its price projection to 9.4 euros from 10 euros. Both
brokerages kept a “buy” rating. The shares dropped 3.2 percent
to 6.89 euros.  Enel SpA (ENEL)  : Barclays Capital reiterated an
“overweight” rating on the shares, saying in a note that
market concerns on regulatory risks are unjustified. The shares
lost 1.5 percent to 4.55 euros.  Eni SpA (ENI)  : BofA Merrill Lynch Global Research
reiterated a “buy” recommendation on the stock, saying it is
“a key deep value play among large cap oils.” The shares
declined 0.3 percent to 16.04 euros.  Monti Ascensori SpA (MSA)  : The company said its
supervisory and management boards will respond to concerns
raised by the company’s auditor about its 2010 accounts. The
company said in a statement that the boards disagree with the
auditor’s report and the supervisory board approved 2010
results. The shares were suspended from trading yesterday.  STMicroelectronics NV (STM)  : Texas Instruments Inc., the
largest analog-semiconductor maker, gave a second-quarter sales
and profit forecast that fell short of analysts’ estimates,
dragged down by sluggish demand for wireless-phone chips from
Nokia Oyj. STMicro shares lost 2 percent to 7.19 euros.  Trevi Finanziaria SpA (TFI)  : The provider of excavation
services got contracts for about 96 million euros. The shares
lost 1.3 percent to 10.07 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Francesca Cinelli in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
James Ludden at   jludden@bloomberg.net  